{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}<!-- [[WP:STRONGNAT]] --> {{Infobox person | other_names = Mario Pagano | image = Mario Pagano.jpg | alt = Francesco Mario Pagano | caption = Francesco Mario Pagano | nationality = [[Kingdom of Naples]] | occupation = {{Unbulleted list | [[Jurist]] | [[Author]] }} | birth_date = {{Birth date|1748|12|08|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Brienza]], [[Province of Potenza]], [[Kingdom of Naples]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1799|10|29|1748|12|08|df=y}} | death_place = [[Naples]], [[Kingdom of Naples]] | alma_mater = [[University of Naples Federico II]] | years_active = 1768–1799 | notable_works = {{Unbulleted list | ''Saggi politici'' (1783–85) | ''Progetto di Costituzione della Repubblica napoletana'' | ''Sul processo criminale'' | ''Esame politico dell'intera legislazione romana'' | ''Discorso sull’origine e natura della poesia'' | ''Gerbino'' | ''Agamennone'' | ''Corradino'' | ''Gli esuli tebani'' | ''Prometeo'' | ''Teodosio'' | ''Emilia'' }} }} '''Francesco Mario Pagano''' (8 December 1748&nbsp;– 29 October 1799) was an [[Italians|Italian]] [[jurist]], [[author]], [[Intellectual|thinker]], and the founder of the Neapolitan school of law.<ref name=CambHistPolTht>''The Cambridge History of Eighteenth-Century Political Thought'', ed. Goldie & Wokler, 2006, p. 765</ref> He is regarded as one of the most influential [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] thinkers.<ref>Fulvio Tessitore, ''Comprensione storica e cultura'', Guida, 1979, p.27</ref> A moderate reformist, he is seen as a forerunner of the [[Italian unification]].<ref>Roland Sarti, ''Italy: A Reference Guide from the Renaissance to the Present'', Infobase Publishing, 2009, p. 457</ref>
==Biography== He was born in [[Brienza]] in the southern [[Province of Potenza]]. He studied at the [[University of Naples Federico II]] under [[Antonio Genovesi]]. At the age of twenty, he became special lecturer in [[moral philosophy]] there, at the same time practising law. He was friend of [[Gaetano Filangieri]], entering the masonry with him, and was elected venerable master of the Neapolitan [[masonic lodge|lodge]] "La philantropia". Pagano was one of the men who powerfully helped Italy in her social and scientific advancement and in the 1790s he had striven more than any other intellectual to give a political form to the 18th century reform tradition in southern Italy.<ref>Girolamo Imbruglia, ''Naples in the Eighteenth Century'', Cambridge University Press, 2007, p. 168</ref>
His work ''Saggi politici'' (1783–85) provided a philosophical history of the [[Kingdom of Naples]], arguing against torture and capital punishment and advocating more benign penal codes. ''Considerazioni sul processo criminale'' (Considerations on the criminal trial, 1787), gave him international popularity and was much praised by ''[[Le Moniteur Universel]]'', the main newspaper of the [[French Revolution|revolutionary France]].<ref>Biancamaria Fontana, ''The Invention of the Modern Republic'', Cambridge University Press, 2007, p. 140</ref>
In 1794 he defended [[Vincenzo Galiani]], [[Vincenzo Vitaliani]] and [[Emanuele De Deo]]&nbsp;– three alleged conspirators against [[Ferdinand IV of Naples|Ferdinand IV]]; after they were sentenced to death, Pagano was deprived of his professorship, arrested, imprisoned and expelled from the kingdom.<ref>[http://www.basilicatanet.it/conoscerebasilicata/cultura/biblioteca/Francesco%20Mario%20Pagano_en.htm Francesco Mario Pagano (1748-1799)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225174541/http://www.basilicatanet.it/conoscerebasilicata/cultura/biblioteca/Francesco%20Mario%20Pagano_en.htm |date=25 February 2008 }}</ref> After fleeing Naples in 1796, he returned in 1799 and drafted the constitution of the short-lived [[Neapolitan Republic (Napoleonic)|Neapolitan Republic]]. The document bore similarities to the [[French Constitution of 1793]] but presented original traits such as the institution of the "body of ephors", an authority who would have overseen the maintenance of the law. It is considered the precursor of the modern [[constitutional court]].<ref>Maria Rosa Di Simone, ''Istituzioni e fonti normative in Italia dall'Antico Regime al fascismo'', p. 111, Giappichelli, Torino, 2007.</ref>
After the fall of the republic, Pagano was arrested and imprisoned in the [[Castel Nuovo]]. He was executed by hanging at the [[Mercato (Naples)|"Piazza del Mercato"]] in Naples, along with other revolutionaries: [[Domenico Cirillo]], [[Giorgio Pigliacelli]] and [[Ignazio Ciaia]].
Pagano's other juridical or philosophical works included ''Progetto di Costituzione della Repubblica napoletana'', ''Sul processo criminale'', ''Esame politico dell’intera legislazione romana'', and ''Discorso sull’origine e natura della poesia''. He also translated works from [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Latin]], and wrote six tragedies (''Gerbino'', ''Agamennone'', ''Corradino'', ''Gli esuli tebani'', ''Prometeo'', and ''Teodosio'') and one comedy (''Emilia'').
