'''Ministers' money''' was a tax payable by householders in certain towns in Ireland to fund the local [[Church of Ireland]] minister.<ref name="jstor25512011">{{cite journal|last=Power|first=T. P.|year=1987|title=A Minister's Money Account for Clonmel, 1703|journal=Analecta Hibernica|publisher=The Irish Manuscripts Commission|issue=34|page=185|jstor=25512011}}</ref><ref name="Thom1853">{{cite book|title=Thom's Statistics of Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yUdVAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA271|accessdate=20 November 2014|year=1853|publisher=Alexander Thom|page=271}}</ref> It was introduced in 1665,<ref name="laws1665">{{cite book|last=Ireland|first=|title=Statutes Passed in the Parliaments Held in Ireland|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=QYFRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA150|accessdate=20 November 2014|volume=Vol.II: 1665-1712|year=1794|publisher=George Grierson, printer to the King's Most Excellent Majesty|pages=150–153|chapter=17th and 18th Charles II., c. 7: An Act for Provision of Ministers in Cities, Corporate Towns and making the Church of St. Andrews, in the Suburbs the City of Dublin, presentative for ever.}}</ref> modified in 1827,<ref name="Britain1827">{{cite book|title=The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QtAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA214|accessdate=20 November 2014|year=1827|publisher=His Majesty's Statute and Law Printers|pages=214–215|chapter=7 & 8 George IV c.34 }}</ref> and abolished in 1857.<ref name="jstor25512011" /><ref>{{cite book |title=Statutes at Large|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WZBKAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA11|accessdate=20 November 2014 |year=1857 |chapter=20 & 21 Vict c.8 "An Act to amend the Act 17 & 18 Vict. c. 11., with a view to the Abolition of Ministers Money in Ireland."|publisher=George Edward Eyre & William Spottiswoode|location=London |pages=11–12}}</ref> The towns affected were [[Dublin]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Limerick]], [[Waterford]], [[Drogheda]], [[Kilkenny]], [[Clonmel]], and [[Kinsale]].<ref name="jstor25512011" /><ref name="Thom1853"/> It was levied as a [[rate (tax)|rate]] of up to one shilling in the pound (i.e. 5%) on the property's rateable value. The [[Real estate appraisal|valuation]], to a maximum of £60, was done by commissioners appointed by the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland|Lord Lieutenant]].<ref name="Thom1853"/> [[Churchwarden]]s appointed by the local minister collected ministers' money on the [[quarter days]]: [[Christmas]], [[Lady Day]], [[Midsummer Day|St John's Day]], and [[Michaelmas]].<ref name="Thom1853"/><ref name="hcc1822"/> A 1723 act<ref name="laws1723">{{cite book|title=2 George I, 1715 – 7 George II, 1733|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rmpBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA234|accessdate=4 March 2015|series=Statutes Passed in the Parliaments Held in Ireland|volume=III|year=1794|publisher=G. Grierson, printer to the King's Most Excellent Majesty|page=234|chapter=10 George I c.3 §19: An act For continuing and amending an act, entitled, ''an act for the better regulating of the parish-watches, and amending the highways in this kingdom'', and for preventing misapplication of public money, and also for establishing a regular watch in the city of Dublin, and to prevent mischief which may happen by graving ships in river Liffey.}}</ref> provided that, in Dublin, the same valuation could be used both for ministers' money and for calculating [[cess]], a separate local rate used for public works and poor relief.<ref name="hcc1822">{{cite journal|last=Select Committee of the House of Commons on the local taxation of the city of Dublin|date=5 June 1822|title=First Report|journal=Sessional papers|volume=7|issue=394|pages=1–3|url=http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/9504/page/209886}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Dudley|first=Rowena|year=1999|title=The Dublin Parishes and the Poor: 1660-1740|journal=Archivium Hibernicum|publisher=Catholic Historical Society of Ireland|volume=53|page=83|jstor=25484175}}</ref> Thereafter, cess rates were often expressed in terms of pence per shilling of minister's money.
Ministers' money was resented because it was a [[regressive tax]] and applied only in towns with a Catholic majority.<ref name="Stowell1854">{{cite book|last=Stowell|first=William Hendry|title=The Eclectic Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=coE3AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA615|accessdate=20 November 2014|year=1854|publisher=C. Taylor|pages=615–616|chapter=The Coalition Government and the Dissenters}}</ref> In rural areas, [[tithe]]s were a similar grievance, and the 1830s [[Tithe War]] ended when the [[Tithe Commutation Act 1838]] replaced tithes with "tithe-rentcharges"; but this did not apply to ministers' money. Another grievance was that the valuations for ministers' money were done infrequently and might not reflect recent improvements or decline in the property or its neighbourhood.<ref name="hcc1822"/> An 1838 proposal by [[Daniel O'Connell]] to bring ministers' money into the terms of the [[Irish Poor Law]] was withdrawn.<ref name="Barrow1838">{{cite book|last=Barrow|first=John Henry|title=The Mirror of Parliament|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iMAMAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA2582|accessdate=21 November 2014|year=1838|publisher=Longman, Brown, Green & Longmans.|pages=2582–83|chapter=Friday 9 March 1838: Poor Relief (Ireland)}}</ref> An 1848 committee of the Commons recommended its abolition,<ref name="Stowell1854" /> and motions to that effect were proposed by MPs [[Francis Murphy (Irish politician)|Francis Murphy]] (1842<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1842/jul/07/ministers-money-ireland|title=MINISTERS' MONEY (IRELAND). (Hansard, 7 July 1842)|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> and 1844<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1844/jul/03/ministers-money-ireland|title=MINISTERS' MONEY (IRELAND). (Hansard, 3 July 1844)|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>) and [[William Trant Fagan]] (six times 1847–54).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1854/mar/09/ministers-money-c-ireland|title=MINISTERS' MONEY. (IRELAND)|date=9 March 1854|work=HC Deb|publisher=Hansard|pages=vol 131 cc552–83|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> A [[petition]] of Cork residents was [[Table (parliamentary procedure)|laid on the table]] of the Lords in 1846.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1846/feb/20/ministers-money-ireland|title=MINISTERS' MONEY (IRELAND). (Hansard, 20 February 1846)|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> In 1854, Sir [[John Young, 1st Baron Lisgar|John Young]], the [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]], introduced an Act<ref name="Britain1854">{{cite book|title=The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=UwobAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA41|accessdate=4 March 2015|volume=17 & 18 Victoria|year=1854|publisher=His Majesty's Statute and Law Printers|pages=41–46|chapter=c.11: An Act to amend the Laws relating to Ministers Money, and the Church Temporalities ''(Ireland)'' Act}}</ref> which reduced the rated charge by one quarter and charged the municipal authority ([[borough corporation#Ireland|borough corporation]] or [[town commissioners]]) rather than the minister with collecting it.<ref name="Scarlett1999">{{cite journal|last=Scarlett|first=Duncan|year=1999|title=Violating the Rubrick Introducing Politics into Divine Worship|journal=Clogher Record|publisher=Clogher Historical Society|volume=16|issue=3|pages=31–32 |jstor=27699434}}</ref> The [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners of Ireland]] forwarded the money from the municipality to the minister, making up the reduction from its own funds.<ref name="Scarlett1999"/> In 1857, Fagan and [[Francis Beamish (MP)|Francis Beamish]] introduced a [[private member's bill]], which was successfully enacted, to replace ministers' money with a direct subvention of ministers by the Ecclesiastical Commissioners. Some members of the Church of Ireland objected to the act as confiscation of church property, and saw it as a prelude to [[disestablishment]], which eventually came under the [[Irish Church Act 1869]].<ref name="Scarlett1999"/>
==Sources== * {{cite book |author=Select Committee on Ministers' Money (Ireland) |title=Report together with the minutes of evidence, appendix, and index |volume=17 |page=118 |id=Paper #559 |series=[[Command paper]]s |date=28 July 1848 |publisher=House of Commons |url=http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/12220}}
